Looks to bowl the yorker but ends up bowling a full toss down the leg side. It does take Latham by surprise as he tries to flick but is late on the shot. Had it been on target, it could have been a wicket.
Another ball outside off, it is not played at.
Outside off, not played at.
A bit of a loose drive that from Latham. It is fuller in length. He plays it ahead of his body and hence, it is not timed well. Still goes through covers for two.
On the pads, Latham looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. Pattinson is appealing but he is the only one doing so. The ball rolls on the leg side. A leg bye is taken.
Another delivery on a length and on off, Latham prods forward and blocks it solidly.
On the pads, Tom Latham works it to mid-wicket.
Just outside off, Latham makes a good leave.
Another back of a length delivery, Williamson plays it late again and gets it through backward point for one.
Shorter and on off, Williamson guides it to point.
James Pattinson is on now! He is making a comeback into the side so he would want to make an impression straightaway.
Outside off, Latham shoulders arms to this one.
That cuts him into half! What a delivery. It lands outside off and Latham looks to defend. He leaves a gap between bat and pad. The ball jags back and sneaks through that gap.
Slightly shorter and around off, Latham leaves it on length.
Angles it into the off pole, Latham keeps it out nicely. Cummins is hoping one ball to straighten after pitching. That has not happened yet.
Back of a length and on off, Latham keeps it out off the back foot.
Cummins comes from aroundthe wicket to the left-hander. He bowls it on off, Latham keeps it out nicely.
Length to end on off, Williamson is solid in defense.
Goes back to bowling it short. Williamson does not play at it.
Top class stuff from Starc! After two bumpers he bowls a yorker now on off, Williamson is up for the challenge as he jams it out.
Another bumper! Williamson ducks under it again. This though is signaled as a wide for height.
A good bumper, Williamson spots it early and evades it.
Just short! Williamson goes after this full and very wide delivery. It goes off the outer half but lands just short of Warner at gully.
Full and outside off, Williamson shoulders arms to it. Good carry to the keeper.

Williamson's away! He opens the face of his bat on this length delivery and guides it through backward point. They take two quickly and go for the third. Complete it. Good running. End of a successful over for Australia.
Outside off, left alone.
Skipper Kane Williamson comes in at number 3, replacing Blundell. 18.2 overs left in the day.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Pat Cummins draws first blood and Blundell's return into the team is not a good one. Cummins goes full and around off, it is not a driving length delivery. The ball holds its line a touch. Blundell goes for the drive but the ball goes off the outside edge and to Paine who makes no mistake. Early wicket for Australia. New Zealand trail by 444 runs.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Shorter in length and outside off, Blundell looks to push it through the off side but it goes off the underedge and on the bounce to second slip.
Outside off, not played at.
Around off, pushed towards point.
Another one in the 140s, watchfully defended.
Down the leg side, Latham misses his flick.
Nice shot. A length ball outside off, extra bounce but TB rises with the bounce and plays it beautifully, placing it between gully and backward point. Three runs taken.
Landed outside off, let through again.

Very good awareness from Tom Blundell. Before this ball, Starc had two men deep on the leg side for him. But Tom expected that this might be a double bluff. And it was. Mitchell bowled it at pace, 145.7 kph, probably expecting Blundell to play at that. But Tom let it through.
An ambitious appeal! This lands on middle and then jags back in. Latham looks to keep it out but misses to get hit high on the pads. An appeal but it is too high.
One more delivery outside off, Latham does not fiddle with it.
Outside off, it is left alone.
A good bumper, Latham sways out of the way at the very end.
On the fuller side and on middle, Latham keeps it out nicely.
Back of a length and on off, kept out.

FOUR! This is a positive start for the Kiwis! Another boundary. On the pads, it is flicked fine on the leg side and the ball races away to the fence. Three boundaries in this over. 12 from it in total.
Still no movement! On a length and on off, Blundell keeps it out.
Change of balls as this one hits a camera when it went to the boundary. It must have lost its shape. Australia would hope the new ball offers some movement.

FOUR BYES! That has taken off out of nowhere! It is a length delivery outside off, Blundell lets it be. It keeps rising after going past the batter. Paine hops but fails to collect it and it goes to the fence behind.

FOUR! That is a lovely shot by Blundell! It is shorter this time and outside off, Blundell gets on top of the bounce and guides it through point for a boundary. First of the game and it is a quality shot. A back foot punch to someone of Starc's pace is not easy.
Very full and straight, Blundell mistimes his drive back to the bowler. That was delivered at 148.7 KPH. Starc is really bowling quick here.
Outside off, looking to curl it back in. It does not. Easy leave for the batter.
BEATEN! Very full and outside off, Latham goes for a booming drive but is beaten. The length was not quite right to play the drive.
One more ball outside off, Latham shoulders arms to this one.
Outside off again, it is not played at. The Australian bowlers haven't got the same movement as the Kiwi bowlers.
On the off stump, Latham is solid in defense.
Outside off, left alone.

In the air... but safe! That was right off the glove! A short one and on the body. Latham looks to work it on the leg side but fails to get on top of the bounce. It hits the glove and lobs behind but lands short of the keeper.
Pat Cummins to bowl from the other end.

BEATEN! That was quick. That even took Paine aback as he collected the ball. It is full and around off, Blundell is beaten for pace as he looks to drive. Paine collects it in front of his face and almost loses balance.
Two leg byes now! A little bit of movement for Starc. Inward movement. The line is very straight though. Blundell looks to flick but misses. It hits the pads and rolls on the leg side. Two taken.
Another couple! This is fuller again and on middle, Blundell works it past square leg and takes two more.
On the pads, Blundell is off the mark now as he works it through mid-wicket and takes two.
A huge appeal from the slip cordon but nothing from the bowler! This is full and on off, Blundell looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Back of a length and on off, it is guided to gully.

No ball! So the wait continues for Australia to bowl their first legal delivery in this game. Latham is also off the mark. It is a length ball around middle, Latham pushes it towards mid on and takes off. The fielder picks the ball up and has a shy at the striker's end but misses. Also, that is a big no ball by Starc. He may have missed his run-up.
The players are out in the middle. Tom Latham and Tom Blundell will open for New Zealand. It is that man, Mitchell Starc, to start off proceedings to Latham. Here we go...

A mountain to climb for New Zealand then. 488 is the target, in a minimum of 168 overs. Highly unlikely that one will see this being hauled down but sometimes, the pitch at the MCG tends to get better in the final innings. The Black Caps of course, will be looking to see off hour by hour and then look at how they are placed. Around 78 overs left today - a decent day's batting should see them get close to 200 - if they forget that they are chasing a target and just focus on playing normal Test cricket. Stay tuned for the final innings.

Describing the innings, it is pretty much similar to how a second innings scorecard looks. No one scoring a half century and everyone throwing away his wicket. Plenty of starts not converted but that was because the batting was done with a sole purpose of giving some rest to the Aussie bowlers. New Zealand toiled hard again and it was that man Neil Wagner, who topped the bowling charts with 3 scalps. Full marks to Trent Boult as well, for coming out to bowl in spite of an injured hand yesterday.

Right. So 31 runs in 9.2 overs this morning. Tim Paine just wanted to have New Zealand out in the middle for some time. Not much progress for Australia today, because they were not able to score quick runs and get to that elusive lead of 500.

OUT! TIMBER! Head has been bowled round his legs. All eyes at the Australian pavilion and there is the signal! AUSTRALIA HAVE DECLARED! Wagner on the other hand, gets his third. It is on the leg pole. Head looks to flick but misses it and the ball hits the leg pole. NEW ZEALAND HAVE A TARGET OF 488!
On the shorter side around off, Head guides it towards point.
Paine is seen taking his pads off so the declaration seems nearby.
Carved away! Full and outside off, Head gets it over point, there is a man in the deep so just one.
Hits this off the middle but finds the fielder at cover.
Another short one down the leg side, Wade pulls it down to fine leg for one.
Another mistimed stroke! Slower short one on middle, Head looks to pull but it goes off the toe-end down to long on for one.
Full and wide outside off, Head looks to go after it but misses. Head is losing his shape everytime he is trying to hit the ball. He is going too hard out there.
Slower short ball outside off, Head is early in the pull, it goes off the bottom half towards the left of the bowler.
One more slower short ball on the body, Head looks to nudge it on the leg side, it goes off the glove though towards the leg side for a single.
On off, Wade guides it to point for one.
Now a bumper, Wade evades it.
Head misses out again! A slower one and it is a full toss. Head swings but the ball dips right at the end. It goes off the inner half through mid-wicket for one.
Outside off, Head strokes it nicely but straight to covers.
A slower short ball on the body of the batter, Head lets it go over him. Watling collects it on the bounce.
On a length and around off, Head guides it through backward point and picks up a single.
On the fuller side, Head strokes it nicely but finds covers.
Slower one outside off, Head is guilty of going too hard at it. He mistimes it towards cover.
On the shorter side, Head tries to pull but the ball does not bounce as much as he expected it to. Gets beaten and it goes over the stumps.
On the shorter side and around off, Wade pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for one.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Landed outside off, played straight to point.
Very full, almost a yorker, driven straight to mid off.
Dropped short, pulled through square leg for a run.
A length ball, around off, coming in with the angle, Travis looks to tuck but gets a thick inside edge onto his hips. The ball drops down and the batsmen take a quick run.
Landed outside off, dabbed to third man for a single.
On the shorter side and on middle, Wade ducks under it.
A short ball and on middle, it is pulled through square leg for one.

Just short again! Good stop in the end by Henry, the sub. Shorter and outside off, Head once again throws his bat at it. The ball flies off the outside edge towards Henry at fly slip. He runs in but the ball then falls just ahead. He puts his body on the line as he dives forward and stops it. One taken.
Head misses out! Shorter and outside off, Head cuts it but can't beat point.
Well bowled! A slower yorker outside off, Head is completely foxed. His feet go nowhere as he tries to put bat on ball but misses.
On the fuller side outside off, Wade strokes it towards cover and takes off. Taylor has a shy at the bowler's end but misses. Wade tries to take another run but it is not on.
Slightly shorter and outside off, once again it takes off after pitching. Head does well though to gently guide it through point for one.
One more short ball outside off, it is left alone.
Outside off, left alone.
In the air... short! One more short ball on the body, Head looks to sway away but realizes it is too late to do so. He plays an upper cut which lands short of Ross Taylor at fly slip for one.
A good short ball, it zips through and is right on the body of the battter. Head hops to defend but then realizes it is getting big on him. Avoids it in the end.
The batsman has stood up on his toes to play that one. The batsmen have run through for a single.
A short one and on middle, Wade ducks under it.

FOUR! Streaky! First boundary of the day. Short and very wide. Head reaches out for it. The ball takes the outside edge and flies over the slip cordon and into the third man fence. 150 UP FOR AUSTRALIA. Lead is 469.
On a length and around off, this one straightens a touch after pitching. Wade manages to guide it towards point for one.
BEATEN! Extra bounce! Shortish and outside off, Wade looks to force it through the off side. He is taken by surprise by the steep bounce. The outside edge of the bat is beaten.
Takes a few steps down the track and then ends up leaving this ball outside off.
Carved away! Full and outside off, Wade opens the face of the bat and squeezes it through backward point. Two taken.
Shuffles right across but Tim Southee smartly bowls it wide outside off. Wade lets it go in the end.
A slower full toss outside off, Head mistimes it to mid on. He may not have picked the slower one there. Lost his shape while hitting that one.
Shortish in length and on middle, Head stays back and keeps it out.
On the leg side, this is worked down towards deep backward square leg for one.
Pulled and done so nicely! Shorter and on middle, Wade gets on top of the bounce nicely. Pulls it all along the ground through mid-wicket for two.
A yorker now and on middle, Wade gets his bat down in time and jams it out.
A bumper but down the leg side, Wade lets it go.
Neil Wagner to bowl from the other end. 13-1-39-2 so far.
Cut nicely! Head has come out with an aggressive approach here. He sees this is short and there is width on offer, slashes, gets it behind point and the batters pick two.
Back of a length around off, Wade taps it towards covers and takes one. His first run today.

Nicely hit but just for one! Fuller in length and outside off, Head gets it right off the middle. Mid off is slightly deep, it runs to his right and keeps it down to one. So New Zealand are already on the defensive. Australia are underway on Day 4!
On the fuller side around off, Head strokes it to covers.
Fuller in length, driven straight back to the bowler.
A good length around off, coming in with the angle, Head dabs it towards point.
We are all set for the day to begin. The players are out in the middle. Tim Southee to start off proceedings to Travis Head. Matthew Wade is the other batsman. Here we go!

For the numbers, Australia lead by 456 runs. The plan might be to try and bat till Lunch and then declare. The Kiwis will be a bowler short, given that Trent Boult has been ruled out of the series. They will hope that Neil Wagner gets a few quick wickets and earns a 5-fer.

Right. On that note, let us now focus to the match on hand. Where is it heading? Probably well beyond New Zealand's reach. The million dollar question would be when would Australia declare. Runs are not an issue, it is the time Tim Paine feels he needs to give his bowlers to take 10 wickets. Scorchers are expected on Sunday and Monday, so bowler management would be on top priority.

Well, normally, we would begin a day by citing the equations, the match situation, the plans, etc, etc, etc. But we shall adopt a different approach today. Because a breaking news has just come from Down Under. PETER SIDDLE HAS JUST ANNOUNCED THAT HE WILL BE RETIRING FROM INTERNATIONAL CRICKET, with immediate effect. A real champion, a real trier. Thank you, Sidders...

Right. What will be Australia's plan on Sunday? Declare overnight? Or come out, bat for an hour, score some quick runs and then declare? There is some forecast of rain on Monday, so Paine would be mindful of that. In all likelihood, Sunday could be the final day of international cricket in Australia this year. Join us on 29th December, 2019 at 10.30 am local (2330 GMT, previous day). ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Australia got off to a decent start in their second innings but have ended up losing 4 wickets before close. Cannot say that the bowling was overly good because runs do not matter at this stage. The batsmen are playing purely for time, to give their bowlers sufficient rest. The talk of the evening would be Neil Wagner slowly getting into the list of bowlers having a wood over Steven Smith. 4/4 in this series!

It all happened in the first hour. Pat Cummins and James Pattinson blew the Kiwi middle order away and they never recovered. Tom Latham fought but that was only as far as keeping the deficit to 319. Only, did we say? Well, it did work in terms of delaying the inevitable as Tim Paine chose to bat again, given the extreme conditions in this Test and also, less gap between this one and the New Year's Test.

An action-packed day then. 4 wickets in the first session, 4 in the second and 4 in the third. An overall tally of 12. The match has progressed rapidly and Sunday might well be the final day of this game.

Phew. That guy was panting. He may not admit it, but Neil Wagner does look tired. But it has just been him who has defined New Zealand's bowling. Single-handedly, he has given them some respectability in this one-sided Test.

Neil Wagner is having a chat with Kath Loughnan. On him having a wood over Smith, with the record reading 4/4, Wagner still feels he does not have the wood on the best batsman in the world, but is thrilled to have dismissed him. Mentions it is a special occasion to take the 200th wicket on this ground and in front of this crowd. He feels sore now and he would want a good sleep and come back fresh on Day 4. Is amazed to see so much of Kiwi support here and hopes to keep fighting and make the fans proud. Is looking forward to coming back on Sunday and give it his best.
Full on middle, pushed towards mid on. STUMPS ON DAY 3, AUSTRALIA LEAD BY 456!
He is giving it his all though. A short ball, banged in the middle of the deck, generating extra bounce, Travis looked to hook but got a top edge which did not carry to fine leg. A run taken.
Around middle, defended watchfully.
Isa Guha on air remarks that probably for the first time, Neil Wagner is looking a bit tired. Strong statement. Just 3 more balls and then he can get a good massage.
Very full, around off, almost a yorker, dug out.
This one is down the leg side and the batsman leaves it alone.
A length ball on middle, Head defends it watchfully.
Outside off, left alone again.
Outside off, not played at.
Short and on middle, Wade pulls it through mid-wicket and bags a couple.
Outside off, it is left alone.
FOUR! Too short and width on offer, it has been put away. Short and outside off, Wade cuts it behind point and it races to the fence.
A length ball, down the leg side, tucked through square leg for a single.
A length ball, down the leg side, Head hops and tucks it past short leg, through square leg for a run.
Down the leg side, flick shot missed.
This one holds off the deck, from a length, TH initially looks to pull, with a hop but then adjusts at the last moment, pushing the ball back down the track.
A bouncer now, ducked under.
A short ball, down the leg side, Head looks to pull but misses.
Full on middle, driven through mid on for a single.
Fuller and on middle, it is driven to mid on.
FOUR! Up and over! Short again, Head waits for it and then at the end, upper cuts it over the keeper and to the fine leg fence.
A yorker now on middle, Head jams it out towards mid-wicket.
Shorter and on off, Head hops and guides it towards gully.
On middle, it is worked through square leg for one.
Outside off, it is left alone.
A quick run as this is worked towards mid-wicket.
On the pads, Wade works it to mid-wicket.
Another bumper, Wade evades it.
On the shorter side again, it is on the body. Wade fails to move out of the way and gets hit on the elbow. Wade is quite tough as that is a sensitive spot but he shows no signs of pain.
On the pads, this is worked fine on the leg side for one.
One more short one and on middle, Head ducks under it.
Down the leg side, Wade looks to flick but misses.
Shorter and around off, Wade pushes it through covers for one.
Very full and on the pads, it is worked towards fine leg for one.
On the shorter side now and on middle, Wade lets it go over him.
Good length and outside off, Head strokes it through covers and takes one.
This is on middle, it is pushed to mid on.
Trent Boult is back into the attack. Just the 6 overs for him so far.
A full toss to end down the leg side. Wade misses the flick.
Bouncer! The batsman ducks under the bouncer at the last moment.
On the body, Head nudges it around the corner and takes one.
Shorter and on the body, Head works it to backward square leg.
On off, Head stays back and blocks it.
Back of a length around off, it is kept out towards cover for one.
Outside off, left alone.
On the middle pole, Head keeps it out.
Outside off, left alone.
On middle, it is worked towards mid-wicket. Wade wants a run but is sent back.
Outside off, not played at.
Wade takes a few steps down the track and squeezes it through gully. Matt Henry, the sub, in the deep, runs to his right, slides and saves a run for his side.
Uppish but safe! A short one which hurries onto the batter. Wade looks to pull but ends up miscuing it towards fine leg for one.
One more short one on middle, Wade sways away from it nicely.
On the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
A bumper, Wade ducks under it.
On the pads, this is worked towards fine leg for one.
Outside off, not played at.
Fullish in length again, this is pushed to the man at mid off.
Back of a length and on off, Wade keeps it out.
Slower one on off, Wade strokes it but finds cover.
This starts outside off, seeing that Wade thinks of leaving it but then it tails back in and Wade defends it at the very end.
This is angled into the batter, Wade blocks it.
Outside off, left alone.
Tim Southee is back into the attack!
Fuller and on middle, Head stays back and defends it out.
Looks to bowl a yorker but ends up bowling a full toss. Head plays it out towards mid on.
Travis Head walks out to bat. A century in the first innings, what is in store for him here?

OUT! TAKEN! 200th TEST WICKET for Wagner and it is of one of the best batters going around. Also, he is the second fastest Kiwi behind Sir Richard Hadlee to get to that milestone. Wagner gets Steven Smith yet again. 4th time in this series. Do we finally have someone who can call Smith his bunny? Well, Wagner may just say that. Once again it is the short ball. Smith looks to pull but ends up miscuing it towards backward square leg. Southee takes a good catch there. Two wickets in quick succession for the visitors.
One more short ball on the body, the batter ducks under it.
Smith goes for another flat-batted swat. This time though he hits it a lot a squarer then he would have liked. It goes to mid-wicket.
Goes short straightaway. Smith lets it go over him.

Matthew Wade comes out to bat now. And Neil Wagner returns to bowl! What timing. 7-0-30-1 so far. Meanwhile, Steven Smith is giving an interview to Mark Howard on the spider cam. On being asked about what would he do in such situation, Smith puts on an innocent baby-looking face, almost as if to say, I don't know. But then, he says that he will aim to play positively with 48 minutes left for the day. On his Tennis forehand short, Steven says that in a situation like this he would want to enjoy himself.

OUT! Caught behind! That was a very late decision from the umpire. Shorter and outside off, not far from the off pole. Burns looks to run it down fine but it is a little too close to the ball to play that shot. It brushes the glove and goes into the mitts of the keeper. There is an appeal, Burns stood his ground, the umpire did not raise his finger but eventually did. Maybe Erasmus thought the edge was pretty obvious and Burns would walk but that did not happen. He had to lift his finger in the end. Burns walks back after a start and Santner gets his first.
On middle, it is kept out.
Slower through the air outside off, it is pushed through covers for one.
Smith comes down the track now and works it with the angle to mid-wicket.
Takes a few steps down the track and hits it down to long on for one.
Flatter and on off, it is pushed to covers.
Another short ball on the body, Smith moves out of the way.
One more short one on middle, Smith lets it go.
Shuffles right across expecting a short one and gets one. He pulls but to leg gully.
FOUR! Smashed! Flat-batted, a lot like a Tennis forehand. It is short and on middle, Smith clears his front leg and hammers it to the wide long on fence.
Shortish from around the wicket and on the hips of Smith. He works it wide of leg gully and takes two.
On the pads, it is worked down to fine leg for one.
On the pads, it is worked through square leg for one.

Turn and bounce! Australia won't mind this. Santner slows it up and lands it on middle, it pitches and then turns away. Burns looks to defend but it goes off the glove, then hits the shoulder and through the vacant first slip region.
Quicker and on middle, Burns goes back to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Flatter and on off, it is pushed to covers.
Down the leg side, Burns misses the sweep.
The master replaces the disciple. Steven Smith comes out to play in an 'Who-cares-how-I-play' scenario.

OUT! He indeed is quite short. For once, Labuschagne gets out for a low score. He works it towards square leg and takes off. Tom Latham picks the ball up and fires it to Santner who collects the ball in front of the stumps and then dislodges the bails behind. An appeal and the umpire takes it upstairs. New Zealand do not seem that excited but they do get excited after watching the replays as it shows that Labuschagne is short. Even the dive does not save him. He walks back disappointed.
Labuschagne seems short! New Zealand do not seem excited but by the first look, it seemed like Marnus is short.
Shorter in length and outside off, evaded.
This is angled into the pads, it is worked through mid-wicket for one. 100 up for the Aussies, they lead by 419.
On the fuller side, Labuschagne pushes it to short cover.
Fuller and on off, it is pushed to mid off.
One more delivery outside off, it is left alone again.
Outside off, left alone.
A shorter ball to end the over, Burns gets right back to block.
Bit of revolutions on this one, pitched outside off, pretty full and then turning away. JB reaches out and pushes it to guess where - point again.
Fuller outside off, draws Joe forward, who comes but loosely plays this with an open bat-face towards point.
Quicker, flatter and shorter, around off, Burns goes back and punches it straight to point.
Landed outside off, pushed straight to cover.
Full and outside off, driven through the covers for a single.
DRINKS!
On the shorter side, Burns pulls it to mid-wicket. A good over for the hosts.
FOUR! Burns might have decided to step on the gas here! Short and outside off, Burns slashes and gets it behind point for a boundary.
Slightly fuller and on off, Burns strokes it to covers.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.

Nearly chops it on! It goes just over! Length and around off, Burns looks to defend but gets an inside edge. It then hits the pad and then changes directions and goes over the stumps. Lucky escape that.
SIX! All the way! That is some shot. Yes, it is right in the arc but it is a glorious shot. Full and on middle, Burns lofts it straight back over the bowler's head for a biggie.
Another single towards cover, this time for Burns.

A direct hit and it could have been interesting! This is pushed to the left of cover and the batters take off. Williamson picks the ball up and has a shy at the keeper's end but misses. Replays show even if he hit, Burns would have been in.
On middle, defended.
Outside off, Burns pushes it towards cover for one.
Flatter and on off, the batter goes back and keeps it out.
Shorter and on middle, Labuschagne pushes it down to long on for one.
One more leave outside off to end the over.
Wide outside off, let through.
Full and outside off, driven straight to mid off.
Smart from Southee but Marnus is prepared. The bowler goes gun barrel straight, expecting the batsman to go across but the Protea stays where he is and flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
And again. Gets across, shoulders arms and then pulls through vacant air.
A length ball outside off, Labuschagne gets a long way across and then plays his pull-cum-leave.
Tim Southee returns. 4-2-2-0 so far.
Flatter and on middle, Burns goes back and blocks it out.
On off, blocked.
Brings out the sweep shot, plays it through backward square leg. The man in the deep makes a lot of ground to his right and keeps it down to three.
Tossed up on off, ML strokes it to covers.
Flatter and on off, Labuschagne pushes it to covers.
Works it with the angle behind square on the leg side. Calls for two and gets two.
Good running! On the pads, this is worked towards deep square leg. It is slightly away from the fielder and two is taken.
Looks to bowl the yorker but slips it down the leg side, Burns looks to flick but misses.
Another short ball and on the body, this is pulled through square leg for one.
This is worked down ti fine leg for one.
A short one, it hurries into the batter, Burns mistimes his pull shot towards mid-wicket for one.
Goes very full now, it is the knuckle ball. Labuschagne strokes it through mid off for three.
WIDE! Way too short and on middle, it goes way over the batter's head. Wided.
Another floated delivery on off, ML pushes it down to long off for another run.
On middle, Labuschagne pushes it back towards the bowler.
One more ball on the pads, Burns works it towards short fine leg for one.
On the pads, it is worked to short fine leg.
Quicker and on middle, kept out.
This is angled into the pads, Labuschagne works it through square leg for one.
A slower short ball outside off, the batter cuts but to point.
A huge shout but that seems to be going down with the angle. Replays show that there was an inside edge too. Full and on the pads, Burns looked to flick but missed to get hit on the pads.
Shorter in length and on the body, this is pulled down to fine leg for one.
Goes full now, ML keeps it out.
One more short ball around off, Labuschagne looks to pull but misses.
Brute of a ball that! It is short and on middle, gets big on Labuschagne. He hops and defends it onto the ground.

Full and outside off, Burns looks to drive this on the walk but the ball takes the outside edge. A defensive field placement and a lack of self-confidence means that there is no slip. This would have carried. The ball goes to backward point.
Arrowed in on off, worked through square leg for a run.
Short and outside off, cut straight to point.
Landed around off, no loop, not much revolutions, no pace, bunted back to the bowler.
Punches this in front of point now, for a single.
Landed around off, punched towards point.
Slower short one on off, ML works it to mid-wicket.
A low full toss on middle, it is worked through mid-wicket for another one.
Shorter and on middle, it is pulled through square leg for one.
On off, blocked.
Welcomes the new batter with a yorker, Labuschagne gets his bat down in time and works it to short fine leg.
Marnus Labuschagne comes in at number 3. 30.5 overs left tonight.

OUT! CAUGHT! Wagner is amongst the wickets again. Warner falls on the first shot he plays out of aggression. It is short and around middle, Warner makes room and slaps it hard but straight to Blundell at cover. Wagner is delighted. Warner will feel a touch unlucky. He had nailed it but straight to the fielder. Australia are effectively 381 for 1.
Flatter and outside off, Warner looks to guide it fine on the off side. Ends up guiding it so fine that it hits the boot of the keeper and then rolls behind towards third man for one.
The batsman has punched the ball off the back foot. They pick up a single.
Comes down the track and then whips it towards wide long on for one.
On off, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Slower through the air, Warner initially looked to play the slog sweep but then defends it out.
A full toss to begin with, it is eased down to long off for one.
Mitchell Santner is on now!
A single to end the over! On the pads, it is worked through mid-wicket.
On the off pole, Warner drops it on the off side and takes one.
Another short one, Warner ducks under it.
On the shorter side again, Warner stays back and defends it onto the ground.
One more short ball but it is down the leg side. Warner looks to help it on its way but misses.
On the shorter side, Warner works it to square leg.
On the stumps, Burns works it to mid-wicket.
Extremely full and outside off, Burns strokes it past the diving cover fielder but to mid off.
Another delivery on a length and around off, blocked.
Just outside off, not played at.
On the off pole, Warner taps it towards cover and takes one.
Outside off again but this time a little closer to the off pole than the last one. Left alone again.
Way too wide outside off, left alone. It has been signaled as a wide.
Lovely ball. Full and around off, swinging in a long way. But Burns is upto it and watchfully plays it towards cover.
FOUR! BOOM! Fractionally short, around off, Burns swivels and pulls this over mid-wicket! Moves to 11, the lead is now 373.
Outside off, driven towards mid off.
50-RUN OPENING STAND UP. Full and outside off, Warner taps it towards cover and takes the single. The wonderful opening combination continues for the hosts.
On a length around off, coming in with the angle, watchfully blocked out.
Landed outside off, swinging away, pushed towards mid off.
Full and outside off, blocked towards mid off.
Outside off, left alone.
Landed outside off, Joe guides it towards gully.
Around off, defended solidly.
Full and outside off, pushed through the covers for a single.
FOUR! Down the leg side, short in length. Warner looks to pull but gets it very fine, just wide of the diving BJ Watling, to the fine leg fence. Moves to 32 from 49 balls.
Full and outside off, Burns looks to defend but the ball swings away and takes the outside edge. Lands just short of gully.
Dropped short, around off, David pulls it through mid-wicket for one.
Full and outside off, this one does not swing. Watchfully pushed back down the track.

EDGED, THROUGH! FOUR. Full and outside off, swinging away, Warner reaches out to push at it. The moving ball takes the outside edge and goes towards second slip. Tim Southee flings himself full stretch to his left but the ball bounces well in front, beats him and races to the third man fence. The lead is now 362.
On middle and leg, tucked through mid-wicket for a run.
A length ball, around leg stump, tucked towards square leg for a single.
Good fielding! Full and wide outside off, Warner hits it through covers. The fielder in the deep, Santner, runs to his left, slides and saves one for his side.
Nicely driven but for no runs! Fuller and on off, Warner strokes it but finds mid off.
One more delivery on a length, it comes back in a touch. Warner pushes it to the left of the bowler.
On off, Warner keeps it out.
This is on middle, Burns looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads. It rolls on the leg side for one.
Fuller and outside off, Burns shoulders arms to this one.
Colin de Grandhomme to bowl from the other end.
He has flicked that off middle. Needed to get bat on ball there. It goes through mid-wicket for one. That swung a long way in.
NO BALL. Wagner oversteps. It is on the pads, Burns looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. It is a massive overstep as well.
Lands it on a length and around off, Burns keeps it out nicely.
Just outside off, left alone.
On middle, Burns defends it on the leg side.
Gets it past the diving fielder and gets three! Slightly shorter and around off, Warner guides it past point and the batters run one less than four.
Starts off with a very full ball on off, Warner strokes it to mid off.

We are back for the final session! 39 overs left in the day so we are in for a long session. The Kiwi players stride out and they are followed by the Aussie openers who will resume their innings. Neil Wagner to start the proceedings for the visitors. Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

It has been slow going from the Australian batters after not enforcing the follow-on! The two openers have took their time and have shown no rush to score quickly. That probably gives you an idea that the declaration may not be coming today. However, it will be interesting to see if they continue in the same manner after the break or opt for a more aggressive approach. New Zealand on the other hand, will try and not let Australia score quickly and for that, they will hope to take wickets at regular intervals. Will the last session go their way or will Australia have another session to their name?
A single to end the session! On the pads, it is worked through backward square leg for one. TEA ON DAY 3, AUSTRALIA LEAD BY 347!
Very full this time and on middle, Burns works it towards fine leg and takes one.
Angles this one into the pads, Burns works it to mid-wicket.
Shorter and around off, Burns pushes it to covers.
One more ball outside off, it is not played at again.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Outside off, Warner is tempted to cut but then bails out.

FOUR BYES! No chance for the keeper! Short and on middle, Warner evades it. It keeps moving away after passing the batter. Watling dives to his right, he gets a hand to it but can't stop it from going to the fine leg fence.
Back of a length and on off, defended.
FOUR! Timed beautifully! A half volley but it still has to be put away. Warner creams it through covers and it races away. First boundary of this innings.
A little too straight, Warner works it through square leg and takes two.
On the middle stump, Warner keeps it out.
On the fuller side, Burns strokes it firmly but back to the bowler.
On the pads, Burns works it to mid-wicket.
On the shorter side, Warner cuts it through point for one.
On off, Warner keeps it out.
Good length and on off, it is pushed to the cover fielder.
On the off pole, blocked.
Colin de Grandhomme is on!
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
On the pads, it is worked through square leg. There is a fielder in the deep so just a single.
Extremely full this time, Warner strokes it to the man at mid off.
Back of a length again, this is guided to the man at point.
Well played! This is on middle, there is extra bounce. Warner does well to take one hand off the handle and defend it.
Jaffa! Unplayable! This is on a length and around off, it moves away a little. Warner looks to play the original trajectory but gets beaten.
On a length again, this is kept out nicely.
The batsman works it down the leg side.
On the fuller side around off, Burns defends it easily.
Outside off, Burns shoulders arms to this one.
One more ball on a length and around off, Burns keeps it out.
Wide outside off, not played at.
Slightly shorter in length and outside off, Warner slaps it through covers. it is not right off the middle but hit well enough to get two.
One more ball outside off, not played at.
Outside off, left alone.
Misfield and a run! Burns pushes it towards cover, Santner misfields and a run is taken.
Almost chops it on! Shorter in length and around off, Burns pushes it at it away from the body. The ball goes off the inside edge, close past the off pole.
This is just outside off, Burns has a poke at it and gets beaten.
A short ball, pulled through mid-wicket for a single.
Around off, this is the inswinger, watchfully kept out.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Full and outside off, watchfully pushed towards cover.
Outswinger outside off, fuller in length, shouldered arms to.
A friendly full toss down the leg side, Burns misses his flick.
Good bowling! After taking a few away, he gets this one to angle back in. Warner realizes that late but does well to get his bat down and keep it out.
One more ball and outside off, Warner initially looks to play but then tries to leave it. Too late though as the ball hits the bat and rolls on the off side.
On the shorter side, Warner hops and keeps it out.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Played that with soft hands! This is on a length and around middle, it moves away. Warner looks to defend with soft hands. It goes off the outer half towards gully.
Burns is off the pair! He pushes at this ball outside off, it goes off the outer half towards gully. The fielder there dives to his right and makes a half-stop. Can't stop the single.
Fullish again, Warner pushes it firmly to the man at covers.
Fuller in length and on off, Warner pushes it to the man at covers.
Goes back to bowling length on off, DW keeps it out.
On the fuller side, Warner strokes it to mid off.
Gets it to shape back in from outside off, does not get it in enough to make the batter play.

NOT OUT! There is an inside edge! New Zealand lose a review quite early. Southee starts this from outside off and then comes back in. It stays a tad low. Warner looks to defend but does so with his bat close to the pad. A huge appeal as Southee feels it is pad first. The umpire shakes his head. Tim really likes it and wants it to be reviewed. Williamson does so. Replays roll in and they show that it is bat first.

Williamson signals the 'T'! Time for a review. A huge appeal for an LBW has been turned down. Southee likes it. Warner is the man in question. There might be an inside edge and the first replay suggests that too.
Another dot as Burns flicks this to mid-wicket.
Still not off the pair is Burns! He gets one on the pads, JB works it to square leg.
Well bowled! Gets it to tail back in from off. Burns gets his front pad out of the way but by just and works it to mid-wicket.
Angles this away from the right-hander. Burns looks to defend but it goes off the outer half towards gully.
On the middle pole, Burns defends it nicely.
Three! A low full toss on the pads, Warner works it wide of square leg and takes an easy three.
Another gentle delivery on the stumps, kept out by Burns.
Outside off, not played at.
On the fuller side, it tails away nicely. Burns keeps it out.
Fuller and around off, Burns pushes it towards cover.
Angled into the pads, it is worked towards mid-wicket for one.
Starts outside off and then gets it to seam back in. Warner keeps it out.
Tim Southee to bowl from the other end.

FOUR LEG BYES! Almost got Burns on the first ball again. This starts on middle and then tails back in. Burns looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. It beats the keeper and goes down to the fine leg fence. An appeal from the bowler but nothing from the umpire.
Gets this one to angle into the batter, Warner looks to block but it goes off the inner half towards fine leg for one. Australia are underway.
Lovey delivery! This starts on off and then moves away a long way. Warner looks to defend but is beaten.
On middle, Warner strokes it to mid on.
Good length, it starts on off and then moves away. Warner stays back and keeps it out.
Starts off with a length ball just outside off, Warner lets it be.

End of another ruthless performance from the Aussies. They are making a habit of this now. New Zealand, on the other hand, have a lot of thinking to do. They have to come up with a better performance in the last Test. A win is what they would want to salvage some pride and for Australia, they would be eager to whitewash the visitors. It is a dead rubber but still a lot to play for in the final Test which begins on the 3rd of January at 1030 local (2330 GMT Previous Day). Till then, take care and goodbye!

TRAVIS HEAD HAS BEEN NAMED THE MAN OF THE MATCH. Feels amazing to contribute to an Australian win. On the best part for him about that innings. Head feels that temperament was the biggest asset as he was able to get through the hard period without throwing his wicket away - something he was struggling in the first Test. Thanks the coaching staff for their continuous support and trusting in him, especially after words of a possible drop for this game.

Victorious Australian captain, Tim Paine, finds the series win very pleasing. Adds that the whole Test was very satisfying, starting from the batsmen's discipline in spite of losing the toss and then the bowlers strutting their stuff. Is happy that the bowlers are sharing the load equally. On his and Head's knock putting together the missed pieces, Paine refuses to admit that, saying that Australia have been playing well but just need to be a bit more consistent. Calls this wicket as very good one for Test cricket, moving sideways on Day 1 but then getting difficult to bat on once the divots started to appear.

New Zealand skipper, Kane Williamson, admits that once Australia got 400, the match became very difficult for his side. Admits that his side could not make use of the surface, in spite of the sideways and lateral movement. Stresses on the accuracy by the Australian bowlers which made the difference. Hopes to improve those come Sydney. On difficulty in winning in Australia. Willy admits that it is difficult and being against a very good opposition can be even more challenging. But also says that the team needs to rise and learn from mistakes. On Wagner's lion-hearted performance, Kane smiles and says that he never gets tired of bowling. Lauds Blundell as well for registering a Boxing Day century. Wishes that his team can start converting its starts and get partnerships.

The Kiwis started their second innings in a good manner but James Pattinson ran through the top order. There were a few partnerships then, Tom Blundell was a part of every stand, he was probably the only positive New Zealand have had in this series. He showed great resilience, fight, grit and played a knock he would remember for a very long time. However, it was too much of an ask and one task which was impossible for a single player to complete. Also, 4th innings, 4th Day so you would expect Lyon to come to the fore. That was the case as he was the pick of the bowlers as he finished with a four-fer.

In reply, the Aussie pacers bundled New Zealand out for a mere 148. Pat Cummins was the star for them with a fifer but Pattinson and Starc supported him extremely well. Australia then decided to not enforce the follow-on. They batted for around 2 sessions, took their lead close to 500 before declaring on the morning of the 4th Day.

End of another dominating performance by the Australians! They have literally blown aside the Kiwis in both the Tests. It is an emphatic series win for them. The only time Kiwis seemed to be in the game was when Boult got Burns in the first over on the first day after winning the toss and electing to bowl but that was it. After that, it was all about Australia. They managed to post a mammoth score in the first innings courtesy a ton from Head and a good innings from Smith.

OUT! That is clean as a whistle! That is the end of the game! Tom Blundell is the last man to get out. End of an outstanding innings. An innings of high caliber. He was going after every delivery now and departs in the attempt to do so. He steps out and hammers this low towards Lyon at mid off who seems to have taken it. The Aussie players start celebrating, the batsman is seen shaking hands with the Australians. The umpires though want to get it checked. They take it upstairs. The SOFT SIGNAL IS OUT! Replays roll in and they show it is a clean catch. AUSTRALIA WIN BY 247 RUNS!
Is that the end of the game? The players are shaking hands but the umpire takes it upstairs to be sure. The SOFT SIGNAL IS OUT!
Shorter and around off, it is hit hard to covers.
FOUR! Comes down the track and makes it into a full toss. It is dragged through wide mid on and a boundary results.
Blundell uses his feet again and whips it straight to mid on.

DROPPED! That was hit hard but it should have been taken! Blundell comes down the track and hammers it back towards the bowler. Labuschagne seems to have taken his eyes off the ball when he needed to watch it closely and the ball does not stay in.
FOUR! Raining boundaries! A short one outside off, Blundell stays back and slaps it through covers for a boundary.

FOUR! HAMMERED! That bursts through the hands of Lyon. Wagner comes down the track and gets to the pitch of it. Slams it back towards the bowler. Lyon looks to catch it but it bursts through his hands and goes down to the long off fence.
Steps down and eases it down to long on for one.
Lyon changes the angle and fires it outside off, it is left alone.
FOUR! Almost an action replay of the last ball! Another one which is short and asking to be hit. Blundell rocks back and pulls it through square leg for another boundary.
FOUR! Short ball and put away! It sits up to be hit. Blundell goes back and pulls it hard over mid-wicket for a boundary.
Pitches around leg, Blundell pads it away. Lyon appeals but nothing from the umpire.
A touch short from this South African born, spinning in again, the other South African tries to work it to the leg side but misses and is hit on the thigh pads.
Massive turn. Full and outside off, Wagner comes half-forward to defend but misses and is hit on the pads. Labuschagne appeals but that was spinning way down the leg side.
Outside off, punched off the back foot for a single through the off side.
Down the leg side, helped fine for a couple.
Action replay of the previous delivery.
Full and outside off, driven straight to cover.
On middle, it is kept out.
On middle, defended.
A couple! Shorter and outside off, this is slapped through covers for two.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Neil Wagner walks out to bat.

OUT! RUN OUT! Southee is out of here now! That is a big, big mix-up. Not sure what the two were doing. I feel both were ball-watching. Southee taps this towards point and then takes a few steps ahead. Blundell is jogging towards the other end but then, for some reason, both stop. Blundell now decides to turn and run to the non-striker's end. In the end both are running to the bowler's end. Pattinson from point gets to the ball and then throws it to the keeper who whips the bails off. Australia now a wicket away and Lyon needs one for a fifer.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.
On off again, Blundell keeps it out nicely.
On off, it is pushed to covers.
Outside off, left alone.
Outside off, this is guided to point.
Quicker and shorter on off, TB stays back and keeps it out.
Well bowled! This lands on off and then turns away a little. Beats the outside edge of Blundell's bat as he tries to defend.

Well, this is interesting. Tim Paine is up for some experimentation. Marnus Labuschagne has been given the ball. The field is spread far and wide. Probably, he wants to lure Tim Southee into mistiming a slog.
Shorter and outside off, Southee cuts it behind point for two.
Tim Southee comes out to bat.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! There goes no. 7 and Australia are now only two wickets away. Still a little more than 30 minutes left for Stumps. Four-fer for Lyon. This is flatter and on off, Santner goes back to defend but the ball turns away, kisses the outside edge and Paine takes a good catch. Paine appeals while Erasmus has got his finger raised almost instantaneously. Santner trudges off. An entertaining stand comes to an end.
Loopy ball on off, Santner keeps it out nicely.
Blundell steps out and works it down to long on for one.
Gets it past cover this time and towards wide long off for one.
Tosses it up around off, it is hit hard towards cover.
On the body, it skids through. Blundell is late on the pull and it hit on the body.
A short delivery which has been pulled away.
On the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
On the pads, it is worked down to fine leg for one.
Back of a length and on middle, kept out.

100 for Tom Blundell! Take a bow, young man. First Kiwi to score a ton at the MCG. Outstanding stuff. A fighting knock of great character. Also, let me remind you that he is not an opener, he bats lower down the order, this is the first time he is opening in a First-Class game and has delivered. Came in the side for the under-performing Raval and has grabbed the opportunity with both hands. He gets there by working this full ball on middle through mid-wicket for one. He takes his helmet off and the whole stadium is up on its feet to applaud the effort.
Blundell on 99... There is a gap on the off side but the leg side is a bit tight.
On middle, kept out.
Blundell onto 99! He steps out and works it through mid on for one.
Down the leg side, extra bounce there. Blundell looks to flick but misses.
On the pads, Blundell works it to backward square leg.
On middle, Blundell flicks it to short leg.
Comes down the track and whips it from outside off towards mid-wicket.
A short one, Santner ducks under it.
Blundell moves to 98! A short one on middle, TB pulls it through square leg for one.
Another length ball around off, Blundell keeps it out nicely.
On the off pole, Blundell blocks it right under his eyes.
A bumper, Blundell watches it go to the keeper.
This is angled into the batter, TB works it to mid-wicket.
FOUR! One bounce boundary! Really well hit this! Santner sees the flight on this one and his eyes lit up. He plays a lofted shot over mid on and then bags a boundary.
On off, blocked.
In the air... safe! There is glove on it. Blundell comes down the track but does not get to the pitch of it. He tries to defend but it hits the glove, then the pad and lobs over leg slip for a run.
On middle, blocked.
On middle, it is worked to short mid-wicket.
The crowd is getting excited. Blundell in within a shot to reach his second Test ton.
Poor ball this! Way too short and outside off, Santner cuts it behind point and bags three. 200 up for the Kiwis, first time they have reached that mark in this series.
A sharp bouncer outside off, Tom looks to pull but misses. Tim Paine leaps to collect but ends up parrying it to Steven Smith at first slip.
That was a good leave. Back of a length outside off, coming in, TB shoulders arms, trusting the bounce on this deck. That did not miss the off stump by much.
EDGED, FOUR! 96 now. Full and outside off, Blundell pushes at it away from his body and gets a thick outside edge. To his luck, it flies wide of first slip, to the third man fence.
Around off, watchfully played out.
Full on middle, pushed towards mid on.
Landed outside off, left alone.
Mitchell Starc comes back onto the field. Must have gone in to pop some pain-killers. Pat Cummins comes back on to bowl now. 15-4-40-0 so far.
Full on middle, Mitchell punches this straight back. Lyon himself gets across to his left and stops it.
On middle and off, watchfully pushed back.
That is a ripper. Flighted outside off, along with pace - 88.8 kph. Santner lunges to defend but the ball pitches and then whizzes past the outside edge. Good take by Tim Paine too.
Full and flat outside off, watchfully defended.
Comes down the track and flicks it past a diving mid-wicket to the man in the deep. Moves to 92. Every run of his is being cheered.
A touch short around off, Blundell looks to work it to the leg side but the ball spins in and hits him on the thighs.
Starc is seen going off! He had some discomfort in his leg. He has gone off to probably eat some pain killers and get it checked by the physio.
Shorter in length and outside off, Santner guides it to point.
Outside off, not played at.
Back of a length and on off, blocked.
A bumper and on middle, it is ducked under.
Down the leg side, the batter looks to flick but misses.
The ball has been square driven by the batsman.
A single as this is eased down to long off.
FOUR! Powerful shot that! He comes down the track and gets to the pitch of it. He whips it and it races to the fence in a jiffy.
Quicker and on middle, defended.
FOUR! A hit-me ball this! A drag down, short and wide outside off, Santner cuts it through point and the ball races away to the fence.
On off, Santner plays it a touch late towards the off side.
Tosses it up on off, Santner lunges forward and keeps it out.
On middle, it is worked with the angle to mid-wicket.
A short ball on middle, Blundell bails out of the pull shot.
Just evades the man at leg gully. On the pads, Santner flicks it uppishly but wide of Labuschagne there. It goes down to fine leg for one.
Lovely delivery! He angles it into the off pole and then gets it to leave the batter. Santner looks to defend but is beaten.
Looks to bowl a yorker but ends up serving a low full toss, it is hit down to fine leg for one.
On off, Bundell keeps it out.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Full and around off, well defended.
FOUR! Lovely placement. Full and outside off, Santner comes down the track, gets to the pitch of the ball and lofts it cleanly over mid off. One bounce and into the ropes. The stand is worth 10 now.
JUST WIDE! Full and around middle, Mitchell looks to defend but the ball goes off the inside edge. Just eludes short leg.
Full and around middle, defended watchfully.
Landed outside off, punched straight to point. It is an umbrella field for Santner.
On a length agian, Blundell keeps it out nicely.
On the off pole, defended.
Outside off, left alone.

NOT OUT! It is going over! Blundell continues to fight on. Excellent use of the review and to be honest, that never looked out. A short one on middle, it stays low. Blundell looks to pull but misses to get hit on the back thigh. An appeal and up goes the finger. Blundell reviews straightaway. Ball Tracker shows it to be going over.
Does Blundell miss out on a ton? He has been given out LBW. He reviews straightaway. It looks high. Yes. Ball Tracker confirms.
Looks to bowl the yorker but ends up bowling a full toss, it is hit to mid on.
Shorter in length and around off, skids through. Blundell looks to pull but is hurried into the shot. He mistimes it towards mid on.
James Pattinson is back! 9-1-33-3 so far.
On middle, Santner stays back and keeps it out.
The straighter one on middle, Santner looks to defend but it goes off the inner half to short leg.
FOUR! Good shot! The back foot punch, not easy to play those. Shorter and outside off, Santner goes back and punches it through covers for a boundary.
On middle, Santner keeps it out nicely.
On middle, this is worked through square leg for a single. He is into the 90s.
Flatter and on off, Blundell keeps it out.
One more short ball and on middle, Santner stands tall and keeps it out.
BEATEN! Another ball shorter in length and outside off, Santner looks to push at it but misses again.
On the shorter side and outside off, Santner plays inside the line and lets it be.
Back of a length and on middle, MS stays back and keeps it out.
One the shorter side on the body, Santner ducks under it.
One more short ball and on the body, it is pulled down towards fine leg for one.
Floats it up on off, Santner is solid in defense.
On off, kept out.
Mitchell Santner comes in at number 8, replacing de Grandhomme. Around 26 overs left in the day, plus an extra half hour if Australia feel they can win the game tonight.

OUT! Caught! Nathan Lyon gets another one. Australia just the three wickets away now. Colin de Grandhomme comes down the track, it is shorter in length and turning back in. Colin looks to whip it but it goes off the inner half towards backward square leg where Warner takes an easy catch. De Grandhomme came out to enjoy himself. He was playing his shots right from the word go and departs in the attempt to do so.
Dropped? Nope, well short and a good stop. On middle, Colin de Grandhomme works it towards short leg. The fielder makes a good stop.
Quicker and shorter outside off, Colin de Grandhomme looks to cut but is beaten.
Nicely played by Colin! He strides forward, leans into the stroke and hits it through covers for two. Played that against the turn. A good shot.
Down the leg side, Blundell lets it go to the keeper.
Over again! On the body, it is shorter. Colin pulls it over the leg gully fielder and down to fine leg for one.
WIDE! Way too short, it goes over the batter's head. Wided.
FOUR! Just over! Good shot in the end! Shorter in length and outside off, Colin de Grandhomme cuts it over the leaping point fielder, Lyon and into the fence.

Top edge but lands short! A short one on off, Blundell looks to pull but gets a top edge, it flies towards Pattinson who runs in from fine leg but it lands short. He does well to put his body in and stop the boundary.
Edged but in the gap! Shorter and around off, Colin de Grandhomme looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge between gully and first slip down to third man for one.
On the pads, Colin works it to leg gully.
Around off, worked through mid-wicket for a run.
Defended off the back foot by the batsman.
Around off, bunted back to the bowler.
Straightaway comes down the track and whips it straight to short mid-wicket.
Colin de Grandhomme walks in at number 7, replacing Watling.

OUT! Caught at leg slip! There comes the wicket and there departs Watling. The footmarks are coming into play now. A lovely delivery by an off spinner. Perfect delivery for his type. First, he gives this plenty of air and seeing that Watling is lured into the drive. He lunges but the ball pitches, landing on the rough created by the footmarks and then spins back in. Takes the inside edge and goes through the gap between bat and pad towards leg slip. Now, credit has to go to Warner here. He would have been blinded but he reacts as swiftly as anyone possibly can and takes a good catch! Made that look simple but trust us, no catch is easy off an inside edge. Australia celebrate but no one appeals. Watling walks off anyway and then umpire Erasmus raises his finger. End of a 72-run stand.
TOP EDGE! SAFE! More luck for BJ. Full and outside off, Watling looks to sweep but the ball spins and bounces off the rough. Takes the top edge but lobs over short fine leg. Two runs taken.
Outside off, Watling mistimes it through covers for one.
One more short ball on middle, Watling evades it nicely.
On the pads, Watling looks to flick but misses to get hit high on the thigh pad.
That almost took short leg's head with it! A short ball and on middle, Blundell hammers the pull, it goes just over short leg and towards mid-wicket for one.

FOUR! Well over! Heart in the mouth moment for Blundell. It is short and on middle, TB looks to pull but gets a top edge, it goes over the outstretched hand of Paine and down to third man for a boundary.
Back of a length and on middle, blocked.
The batsman works it down the leg side.
Changes to over the wicket and lands it on off, defended.
FOUR! Watling getting into the act now! He too comes down the track and works it with his wrists and hits it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Steps out one more time. Lyon fires a full toss around off, Blundell whips it towards long on for a quick run.
Comes down the track again, does not get to the pitch of it this time. Blocked.
FOUR! Up and over! Excellent use of the feet and gets the desired result. He hits it with the turn over the mid-wicket region for a boundary.
On the pads, it is worked towards mid-wicket for no runs.
On the middle pole, Watling looks to defend but it goes off the inner half to short leg.
Slightly short and angling away from off. Watling drops his hands and lets it go to the keeper.
Full and outside off, left alone.
On the shorter side, Blundell plays the hook shot by getting on top of the bounce. It goes towards fine leg for one.
Back of a length and on off, Blundell defends it onto the ground.
Mitchell Starc is back! He has been a little wayward today, needs to get it right here. 11-3-43-0 so far.
On middle, kept out.

FOUR! Deft! Shorter in length and quicker outside off. Watling plays it late and down towards third man. Cummins from backward point gives it a chase, slides and pushes it back in. The umpires go upstairs to check if the stop is clean and replays show he has touched the ball and the ropes at the same time.
On middle, kept out.
On the pads again, this is worked to the right of the short leg fielder who dives and stops it.
Shorter and on middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
Flatter and on off, Watling blocks it out.
On the off pole, blocked.

50-run stand up between Blundell and Watling. Consecutive fifty-run stands for New Zealand in this innings. This one though needs to go longer. Full and outside off, Watling drives it through covers and bags three.
Landed outside off, a touch wide, left alone.

Good stop. Full and outside off, BJ drives this down the ground but Matthew Wade at somewhere between a slightly wide silly mid off and a fine short cover makes a half stop, parrying it towards mid on.
A length ball this time, blocked back watchfully.
A bouncer on middle, comfortably ducked under.
Fired outside off, the arm ball, let through.
Full and around middle, defended in front of short leg.

This was coming. Good batting from Blundell but Lyon will not mind. The opener has been stifled for runs post Tea and the Aussies are challenging him to earn his runs. Tom comes down the track, trying to disturb Lyon's rhythm. Gets to the pitch of the ball and whips it over mid-wicket for a couple.
A touch short, whipped straight to backward square leg.
A touch short, punched towards mid on.
Full and outside off, watchfully defended.
Landed outside off, left alone.
Well, what happened there? Nigel Llong signalled the over but was then informed by someone that there is a ball left. Apologizes to the bowler and then smiles.
Full and around off, solidly defended.
Outside off, on a length, played straight to point.
Full and outside off, pushed straight to short extra cover.

EDGED, DOES NOT CARRY! It seems like an edge has come after ages. Full and outside off, Watling pushes at it but the ball takes the outside edge. Goes behind but lands short of Steven Smith at second slip.
A length ball around off, worked through mid-wicket for a single.

'CATCH!' is the cry from Paine. But the ball lands safely. Short and outside off, Watling quickly goes back to pull but the ball comes on faster than his anticipation. Hence, he gets a top edge which lobs over short fine leg. Two runs taken.
Jumps down the track this time, gets to the pitch of the ball and pushes it towards cover.
Full and around off, pretty flat, watchfully defended.
Down the leg side, spinning in, worked straight to short fine leg.
A touch short, BJ goes back and looks to work it through mid-wicket but Matthew Wade at short leg uses his reflexes to get his hand to the ball and parries it to short mid-wicket.
Full and around middle, darted in, worked watchfully in front of short leg.
Back of a length and on off, TB pushes it to covers.
Solid drive but straight to the bowler. Full and on off, Blundell hits it back to the bowler.
Just outside off, not played at.
On the fuller side, Blundell drives but to cover.
Another back of a length ball around off, Blundell keeps it out.
Back of a length and on off, Blundell pushes it to mid off.
Pat Cummins to bowl from the other end. 12-3-36-0 so far.
Shorter in length again, this is guided to point.
On middle, Watling stays back and works it to mid-wicket.
Loopy ball outside off, it is driven to covers.
Works it with the turn to mid-wicket.

Is that a drop? Maybe. A tough chance though. It lands on off and it turns back in. It takes the inside edge, then the pads and lobs towards silly point. Labuschagne dives forward with one hand stretched forward but it only brushes the fingers.
On middle, it is worked to short leg.

We are back for the final session! Out come the Australian players and they are followed by the two Kiwi batters Watling and Blundell. 5 wickets is what the Aussies need as Boutl won't be batting to end the game today itself. Will we see a Day 5 in this game? We will have to wait to find out. For now, it is Nathan Lyon who will start proceedings for the Aussies.
... Day 4, Session 3 ...

Kath Loughnan has a chat with Nathan Lyon. On bouncing back to take Nicholls' wicket after being hit for a six on the previous ball, Lyon says that there is not enough on the wicket so it is a challenge for the bowlers to induce mistakes. On whether Australia can push for victory in the final session, Gary says that the Kiwis possess a quality batting line-up but the hosts will try their best.

The session started off with Nicholls and Blundell playing well. The two added a 54-run stand before the former was dismissed to Lyon. Blundell then got to his half ton and after that the opener started playing his shots. He has scored really freely and him and Watling are amidst a good partnership. The two however, need to go on. The Australian bowlers have found it tough in this session. There is hardly any purchase on the wicket. They though need to be patient as they still have the upper hand. To whom will the last session belong?

An excellent session for the Kiwis! The two batters walk out to a standing ovation from their fans. They have really entertained the crowd with some really good shots, albeit they are still way behind in the game.
On a length and around off, blocked. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 4!
FOUR! Past the dive of the fielder and another boundary! It is full and on off, Blundell transfers his weight onto the front foot and creams it past the mid off fielder for a boundary.
Back of a length and on off, Watling keeps it out.
On the fuller side, it is driven to covers. Two fielders in that region and both catching. So Cummins is bowling to his field here.
On middle, defended.

FOUR RUNNING RUNS! Runs flowing at the moment! On the fuller side outside off, Blundell drives it past short cover-point. The fielder there dives and gets a hand to it. Can't stop the batters from running four though.
Back of a length and around off, Watling guides it to point.
This is angled into the pads, it is worked through square leg for one.
Outside off, it is left alone.
FOUR! Hammered! Take that, Pattinson says Blundell. Shorter and on middle, Blundell picks the length early and pulls it hard behind square on the leg side for a boundary. Consecutive boundaries.
FOUR! Full and on the pads, too straight and Blundell loves it there. It is flicked through mid-wicket for a boundary.
OHHH! This is just outside off, Blundell hangs his bat out and gets beaten. He could have left that, it was quite wide.
James Pattinson comes back! 8-1-24-3 so far.
On the shorter side, Blundell pulls it through square leg for one.
On middle, it is worked towards mid-wicket for another single.
Back of a length and on off, kept out.
Almost! This lands on off and then comes back in. Blundell looks to defend but it goes off the inner half on the leg side. One taken.
On middle, it is worked wide of mid on for one.
On the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket. Starc gives it a chase from mid on and the ball slowing down near the rope making Starc's job easy. Three taken.
Pat Cummins is back! 10-3-21-0 as of now.
The batsman works it down the leg side. One run added to the total.
On middle, kept out.
Catch it is the call but not sure if it is off the bat! Flatter and on middle, it turns back in. Blundell looks to flick but misses to get hit on the body. The ball lobs well wide of short leg.
Blundell comes down the track and defends it into the hands of silly point. He gets back in, the fielder then scores a direct hit at the striker's end.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
On middle, kept out.
Nathan Lyon is back! 6-3-11-1 so far.
FOUR! That is some shot to get off the mark! Full and on middle, Watling shows the full face of the bat and creams it through mid on for a boundary.
Back of a length, Watling keeps it out.

Fifty for Blundell! He is fighting a lone battle here. A huge round of applause for him from the crowd and well deserved. His maiden in Tests. Also, the last time he scored a half ton, he went onto convert it into a ton. Needs to do the same here. He gets there by squeezing this through backward point for three.
A little too straight, it is worked through mid-wicket for two.
Outside off, not played at.
Slightly fuller and around off, blocked.
This lands on middle, it jags back in. Watling looks to work it on the leg side but misses to get hit on the pads.
A good short one, the batter ducks under it.
On middle, it is worked to mid-wicket.
On middle, it is kept out.
On a length and around off, it is guided towards point.
Shorter and on middle, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Pat Cummins is back! 9-3-20-0 so far.
A low full toss on middle, Watling works it uppishly but well wide of mid-wicket. BJ wants a run but is sent back.
The change of balls almost does the trick. Fuller and around off, it comes back in. Watling looks to drive but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
New balls please! Australia get their ball checked. The umpire gets the 8-ball gauge out. It does not pass through and the bag of balls has been called out.
Shorter and around off, it is pushed to covers.
Lands outside off and it comes back in. Not enough though to make the batter play.
On a length again and on off, defended nicely.
On a length and around off, blocked.
James Pattinson is back on! 6-0-15-3 so far.
A dot to end as this is blocked out.
Well played in the end! Blundell comes down the track and Lyon slows it up outside off. It seems like Blundell is beaten by the flight but he does well to keep it out in the end.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.
Flatter and on middle, kept out.

Would that have been out? It would have been very close. Blundell comes down the track and hits it hard back towards the bowler. Lyon looks to deflect it back towards the stumps at his end but misses. Watling dives to make it back in. However, judging by the replays, it seems Watling might have been in.
On the pads, it is worked to square leg.
Extremely wide outside off, Watling initially looks to put bat on ball but then seeing how wide it is, lets it go.
Extremely full and on the pads, Watling works it to mid-wicket.
Excellent shot! Fuller and on middle, Blundell strokes it past mid on. He just shows the full face of the bat and uses the pace of the bowler. Gets three.
The batsman has punched the ball off the back foot.
FOUR! Just wide! Shorter and on the body, Blundell looks to pull but the ball kisses the glove and goes just wide of the diving keeper and down to the fine leg fence.

NOT OUT! The pitching is indeed the issue! It is outside leg and you need not look any further. Australia lose a review. It is on the pads, Blundell misses the flick shot. It hits the pad and an appeal goes up. The umpire shakes his head. Paine and Starc have a chat and then the former signals the 'T'. Replays roll in and it shows the on-field call is the right one.
A huge appeal for an LBW has been turned down! Starc and Paine have a discussion and Australia review. It looks to be missing leg. The pitching can also be an issue.
Around middle, well defended.
Full on middle, worked in front of short leg.
On middle, punched back to the bowler
Around off, defended from the crease.
BJ Watling comes in at number 6, replacing Nicholls.

OUT! STUMPED! No wonder why Tim Paine did not appeal. Because the back foot did not come back in at all. Lyon has broken through the 54-run stand. Full and outside off, plenty of flight, Henry lunges to defend but misses. Paine collects and quickly whips the bails off. Does not even appeal and is celebrating in jubilation. The umpire refers it upstairs and replays show that Nicholls did lunge to defend but then could not get his back foot in at all. It stayed on the line. End of a scratchy innings.

STUMPING APPEAL! Is Nicholls gone? Paine is not even appealing. He is supremely confident and is celebrating. Nicholls is walking off. This is referred upstairs and replays show that the foot never came back into the crease. On the line. Gone!
SIX! Clean as a whistle! Full on middle, Nicholls comes down the track and lofts it beautifully, with a straight bat, over long on. Nice way to bring up the 50-run stand. A resistance at last.
One more on the pads, Nicholls works it uppishly but wide of short leg and towards square leg for one.
Short and outside off, not played at.
On off, Nicholls shows the full face of the bat and keeps it out.
On the shorter side and on middle, HN nudges it to mid-wicket.
On the body, it is worked behind square on the leg side for one.
Shorter in length and on middle, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Nicely bowled! Slower through the air and on off, Nicholls comes forward and keeps it out nicely.
On the shorter side, this is worked towards mid-wicket.
From around the wicket now, it lands on off and goes on with the angle. Blundell looks to defend but it goes off the outer half towards short third man for one.
Comes down the track and works it to square leg.
Almost plays it on! Shorter and quicker outside off, Tom looks to defend but the ball hits the bottom, bounces behind him and goes just beside the stumps.
Tosses it up on off, Blundell defends it onto the ground.
Hits the glove! Another short ball on the body, Nicholls looks to flick again but the ball hits the glove and falls on the leg side.
On the shorter side and on the body, Nicholls works it to square leg.
WIDE! Way too short, Nicholls ducks under it. Wided.
Another back of a length delivery, HN is solid in defense.
Back of a length and on off, Nicholls keeps it out.
Uppish but safe! Shorter and on the body, Nicholls works it uppishly but wide of backward square leg for two.
Soft leading edge! Angled into the pads, Nicholls looks to work it on the leg side but closes the face of the bat early. A soft leading edge is induced towards cover.

DRINKS BREAK. David Warner is now giving an interview. He says it is always going to be difficutl to get guys out, the two out there are playing well and they are hopeful to force and error and get them out. On the retirement of Peter Siddle he says he has had an excellent career, he is a lovely person and he wishes him all the best for the future.

Direct hit and it would have been very close! Nicholls works it towards mid on and sets off. Cummins there gets to the ball quickly and releases it quickly. Has a shy at the non-striker's end but misses. Even the dive from Nicholls would not have saved him.
Loopy ball on middle, this is pushed back to the bowler.
One more single! Blundell again uses his feet and flicks it past Matthew Wade at short leg, to his right and through square leg for one.
Shorter and around off, Blundell stays back and plays it with the turn to short leg.
On the pads, it is worked towards mid-wicket for one.
Blundell comes down the track and then works it towards mid on for a single.
On a length and around off, it is kept out. End of an eventful over.
15 runs in the over now and a ball to go! This one is flicked through square leg for one.
FOUR! Third boundary in the over! Shorter in length and on the body, Blundell manages to tickle it fine on the leg side for another boundary. So after three maidens, a huge over this for the Kiwis.
Short and down the leg side, it is left alone.
